The Trojan Horse of Europe
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Emergency funds will have to be provided.
Conditions will have to be attached.
The Greek government will make the usual promises.
Cela devrait permettre au gouvernement grec de servir sa dette.
Les marchés vont se calmer.
Les conséquences à plus long terme ne seront pas rédhibitoires, mais il y aura des problèmes à venir.
Certains diront que l’erreur fatale fut d’avoir autorisé la Grèce à adopter l’euro en premier lieu.
Il était pourtant déjà évident que le pays n’était pas prêt.
Its fiscal policy was already out of control when it joined the monetary union in 2001, and its unions were already pressuring for Greek wages to align with those in Europe, despite lagging productivity.
But this response is too simplistic, as such signs of dysfunction are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with a 20% unemployment rate and abyssal budget deficits, sees Greece as a mirror of its own future.
And if not, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy are doing somewhat better.
These countries, just like Greece, must face large budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot devalue their currency to boost exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to seek aid.
All of this raises one question: wasn't the real mistake in creating the euro?
In the sense that I was one of the few Americans who encouraged the idea of a European currency, you would be justified in asking me: are you reconsidering your initial position?
My answer is no, the creation of the euro was not an error, but it could well become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway along the path to a viable monetary union.
If it does nothing, the next crisis could well make this one look like a walk in the park.
If Europe wants to complete its monetary union, it will have to create its own emergency financing mechanism.
Today, members of the Union cannot provide aid to Greece except by circumventing the regulations that prevent them from granting a loan except in the case of natural disasters or circumstances beyond the control of a country.
This exacerbates the uncertainty.
When European leaders provide aid, public opinion and the markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems result from the Lisbon Treaty, then it must be amended.
Furthermore, aid should not be granted solely under certain conditions, but should be accompanied by temporary national budget control by a committee of « experts » appointed by the European Union.
The history shows that simple promises made by the beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, the countries subjected to such measures will express their outrage.
But no one forces them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Note that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the defunct Stability and Growth Pact.
We could also ask ourselves the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily placed its budget in the hands of an expert specifically appointed by President Barack Obama's administration?
In fact, it would not bother them too much.
The expert would not be of Californian origin, but American.
The public would understand that he would act in the interest of the state of California as well as that of the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, from whom these orders would emanate, would reassure them.
Europeans do not do this kind of thing because they first and foremost see themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the « sovereignty prerogatives » of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant given its history during the second world war, especially in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties, but also closer political ties.
Those who have a solid emergency aid mechanism will really have to account for their actions.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of Chancellor Angela Merkel's party hates this kind of rescue because they know well who will be responsible.
Germans oppose anything that resembles European political integration.
But Germany also has its share of responsibility in this crisis.
It wanted an incredibly independent central bank that was not obligated to account for its actions, but today this bank has adopted a monetary policy that is too excessive, thereby critically worsening the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
Germany's huge current account surpluses further aggravate their situation.
Moreover, its fiscal stimulus measures were not sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has significantly benefited from the creation of the euro.
She should be made to pay.
She should encourage the creation of an emergency loan facility, as well as political integration to make it possible.
She must provide more budgetary support.
Isn't she best positioned to push for a more accountable European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan Horse that leads Europe towards more mature political integration.
We can only hope.
